Adult light morph.description: Parasitic Jaegers are larger and heavier-bodied than Long-tailed Jaegers, with a more forceful flight style. Breeding adult Parasitic have long tail feathers, but they're not as extreme as Long-tailed Jaegers' tails.

Adult dark morph.description: Parasitic Jaegers tend to flash more white in the wing than Long-tailed Jaegers. Parasitic's bill is longer and thinner than Long-tailed's.

Immature light morph.description: Parasitic Jaegers are heavier bodied and have broader wings with less buoyant flight than Long-tailed Jaegers. Parasitic shows more white in the wings; Long-tailed Jaegers usually have the white confined to the outermost couple of primary feathers.

Adult light morph.description: Pomarine Jaegers are considerably larger than Long-tailed Jaegers, with a more burly shape and a correspondingly forceful flight style, quite different from Long-tailed's light, buoyant flight.

Adult dark morph.description: Breeding Pomarine Jaegers have twisted, spoon-shaped feathers unlike the very long tail streamers of Long-tailed.

Immature light morph.description: Pomarine Jaegers are larger and more barrel chested than Long-tailed Jaegers. They have large white flashes in the wing, much more extensive than the white in Long-tailed's outer 2 or 3 primaries.

Dark morph.description: Northern Fulmars fly with stiffer, straighter, and narrower wings than jaegers. They tend to take a few quick wingbeats followed by a glide, unlike the acrobatic, flapping flight of jaegers.

First winter (Iceland).description: Most gulls are larger, bulkier, slower, and less acrobatic than jaegers. Gull plumage can be extremely variable, but they never show the white flashes in the dark outer wing characteristic of jaegers.
